Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved, peeled and thinly sliced).

Heat a drizzle of oil in a deep #saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting #lid{}) on medium heat.

Once hot, add the onion, season with @salt{} and @pepper{} and fry, stirring occasionally,
until golden and soft, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic{2%cloves}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Once the onion is golden, stir in the @cider vinegar{15%ml} and @sugar{1/2%tsp} and allow the
vinegar to evaporate, ~{1%minute}.

Stir the garlic into the onion and fry for ~{1%minute}, then add the @basmati rice{150%g} and
stir until coated, ~{1%minute}.

Add the @vegetable stock paste{15%g} and @water{300%ml} and bring to the boil. Once boiling,
turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and
leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

Meanwhile, sprinkle the @lemon & herb seasoning{1%sachet} over the @British chicken breast{240%g}(diced) and
season with @pepper{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat. Once hot, add the chicken
and fry until golden brown and cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} each side.

Add the @honey{1%tbsp} and turn the chicken so it's nicely glazed, then remove from the heat.
Cover to keep warm.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and utensils after handling raw meat. Cook so there's no pink in the middle.

Once the rice is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{} and stir in the @peas{120%g}, @chipotle paste{20%g}
(add less if you'd prefer things milder) and @butter{20%g}.

Pop the lid back on and allow the peas to heat through, ~{1%minute}.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Share the chipotle pilaf between your #bowls{} and drizzle over the @soured cream{75%g}.

Top with the glazed chicken to finish.

Enjoy!